text:
A close view of the front wall of 10 Vandam Street, south side, west of MacDougal Street, a three-story frame house faced with brick. Alterations are now being made while the lot which adjoins it on the right is being excavated for the foundations of the Butterick Building. This house will be demolished between 1922 and 1925. October 24, 1902.

Wurts Brothers.

10 Vandam Street, south side, west of MacDougal Street, a three-story frame house, faced with brick, photographed during alterations made when the lot adjoining at the west was being excavated for the foundations of the new Butterick Building. This little house will be taken down between 1922 and 1925.
October 24, 1902.
Wurts Brothers.

29 to 7 Vandam Street, old residences on the south side, west of, and looking towards MacDougal Street. There is a little break between No. 23 and No. 21, the last of the group with dormer windows. Just east of No. 21 are three frame houses faced with brick, Nos. 19-15. Then there is another little gap, followed by the double house 13-11 Vandam Street, which has a carriage entrance in the center of the house, under the round window, for carriages to go through to the back yard. Compare 48-50 King Street. No. 9 has two dormer windows. Beyond No. 7 is No. 5, a seven-story tenement house.

About 1918.

New York Sun staff photograph.
Gift of E. M. Jenks.

13-11, 9 Vandam Street, north side, west of MacDougal Street. The former building is a double house with a now obsolete carriage entrance and driveway through the building to the back yard. 48-50 King Street (q.v.) is another house of this type. No. 9 Vandam Street is the little house with the dormer windows. 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
